### Meaning

# Combined course hardness index. To capture overall course difficulty beyond any single factor, a composite hardness index was built from four z-scored components: total elevation gain, the rank of net elevation change (used in place of a raw z-score, since Boston's exceptionally large net downhill would otherwise dominate the index — see methodology note above), deviation from a 10°C reference temperature, and average wind speed. Boston emerges as the clearly hardest course (hardness = 2.49), consistent with its combination of substantial climbing, an extreme net elevation drop, and moderate wind. Tokyo and London follow as moderately hard, driven respectively by wind exposure and a comparatively large temperature deviation. Chicago is the clearly easiest course (hardness = -3.82), sitting near the mild end on every component simultaneously — flat, calm, temperate, and with minimal net elevation change — which the additive scoring method compounds into an especially low combined score. This is a property of summed composite indices worth noting: a course that is consistently mild across several dimensions can score more extreme overall than one that is extreme on a single dimension alone.

