### Meaning "Combined course hardness showed a stronger relationship with winning time than with the top-10 pack average. For women, hardness was significantly associated with slower winning times (+37.7 seconds per unit, p = 0.012); for men, the effect was similar in direction and comparable in magnitude but fell just short of conventional significance (+26.2 seconds per unit, p = 0.061). This mirrors an earlier finding using elevation alone: harder conditions appear to disproportionately affect whoever is racing to win, rather than uniformly slowing the elite field. Taken together, these results — observed independently with two related hardness measures — suggest that pack depth may buffer top-10 performance against course difficulty in a way that individual winning efforts are not buffered."

